{"schema": {"fields":[{"type":"integer","name":"index"},{"type":"string","name":"author_association"},{"type":"string","name":"body"},{"type":"datetime","name":"created_at"},{"type":"string","name":"html_url"},{"type":"integer","name":"id"},{"type":"string","name":"issue_url"},{"type":"string","name":"node_id"},{"type":"datetime","name":"updated_at"},{"type":"string","name":"url"},{"type":"string","name":"user"}],"pandas_version":"0.20.0","primaryKey":["index"]}, "data": [{"index":0,"author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"To expand on what @leweaver said: We've also determined that the next revision of WebVR (which should be the one that sticks around) will have forced context loss as a core concept of using WebGL with a VR device. [Pull request here.](https:\/\/github.com\/w3c\/webvr\/pull\/226)\r\n\r\nThe TL;DR version is that contexts used with WebVR devices will need to have a compatibility bit set on them. You can do this two ways. First, with a context creation arg, like so:\r\n\r\n```js\r\nlet gl = glCanvas.getContext(\"webgl\", { compatibleVrDevice: vrDevice });\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis won't cause context loss, but may not be appropriate if you don't know ahead of time that the user will be using a specific `VRDevice`. The second method is a bit more disruptive:\r\n\r\n```js\r\nlet gl = glCanvas.getContext(\"webgl\");\r\n\r\n\/\/ Some time later...\r\ngl.setCompatibleVrDevice(vrDevice).then(() => {\r\n    \/\/ If the VRDevice is connected to a different GPU than the one\r\n    \/\/ the WebGL context was created with this would have forced\r\n    \/\/ a context loss. The promise only resolves when the context\r\n    \/\/ has been restored. If the page doesn't handle it the promise\r\n    \/\/ is rejected.\r\n});\r\n```\r\n\r\nObviously the context loss case won't be triggered every single time, and many devices (such as mobile) may never see a context loss. But devices with multiple GPUs (even laptops with an integrated\/discreet pair) could hit this path frequently.\r\n\r\nIdeally Three.js can provide some mechanisms for dealing with context loss and promote it as something that developers need to pay attention to, otherwise you'll get a lot of devs who test their content on a single-GPU system and say \"It Works!\" and then wonder why things fail on some systems when their content is released in the wild.","created_at":"2017-06-07T21:19:32.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/11435#issuecomment-306928310","id":306928310,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/11435","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDMwNjkyODMxMA==","updated_at":"2017-06-07T21:19:32.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/306928310","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/toji\/following{\/other_user}","events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/toji\/events{\/privacy}","avatar_url":"https:\/\/avatars2.githubusercontent.com\/u\/805273?v=4","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/toji","gists_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/toji\/gists{\/gist_id}","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/toji","subscriptions_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/toji\/subscriptions","node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjgwNTI3Mw==","repos_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/toji\/repos","received_events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/toji\/received_events","gravatar_id":"","starred_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/toji\/starred{\/owner}{\/repo}","site_admin":false,"login":"toji","type":"User","id":805273,"followers_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/toji\/followers","organizations_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/toji\/orgs"}},{"index":1,"author_association":"OWNER","body":"Okay. Basic support added. Works in most of the cases but a few things break when restored (sprites, lensflares, etc). I'll be fixing them over the next days.","created_at":"2017-06-30T00:47:48.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/11435#issue